Part F: Security Reflection

Security Reflection

1. What cybersecurity risks did you identify in your own digital habits?

During this security audit, I identified several cybersecurity risks in my digital habits.
I noticed that I do not always check security settings on all my online accounts regularly.
Sometimes software updates are delayed, which may leave devices vulnerable to security threats. 
I also realized that relying only on passwords without enabling Multi-Factor Authentication (MFA) on every account can increase security risks.
Additionally, clicking links or downloading files without carefully verifying their source can expose users to phishing attacks and malware.

2. What security improvements will you implement immediately?

To improve my cybersecurity, I will start using strong and unique passwords for all important accounts. 
I will enable Multi-Factor Authentication wherever it is available to add an extra layer of protection.
I will also ensure that my operating system and applications are updated regularly. Furthermore, I will be more
cautious when opening emails, clicking links, and downloading files from unknown sources. Regularly reviewing account
security settings will also become part of my routine.

3. Why is cybersecurity important in today's world?

Cybersecurity is important because people rely heavily on digital technology for communication, education, banking,
shopping, and storing personal information. Cyber threats such as phishing, malware, ransomware, and data breaches can 
result in financial loss, privacy violations, and data theft. By following good cybersecurity practices, individuals and 
organizations can protect sensitive information, reduce risks, and create a safer digital environment for everyone.
